      Are loans securities?
   =20
 =20

Traditionally, in US law, a bond is a security=C2=A0and a bank loan is not.=
 If a company borrows money by selling bonds to the bond market, it has to =
follow securities laws; the theory is that bonds are sold publicly to lots =
of different unrelated investors, who will want the disclosures and legal p=
rotections of the securities laws. If a company borrows money by taking out=
 bank loans, it does not have to follow securities laws; the theory is that=
 loans are negotiated directly with a handful of banks who are sophisticate=
d, know the company well and do not really need the protections of securiti=
es laws.=C2=A0
In modern markets=C2=A0that is not particularly true. =E2=80=9CBank loans,=
=E2=80=9D these days, are   often syndicated loans sold to hundreds of inve=
stors, many of whom are hedge funds or collateralized-loan-obligation manag=
ers or otherwise not banks. Bonds, meanwhile, are mostly sold to big instit=
utional investors too, and there is some overlap between the loan and bond =
investor bases. It seems a bit strange and outdated to treat loans and bond=
s differently, and so you sometimes come across people who argue that loans=
 should be securities, or people who are surprised to learn that they aren=
=E2=80=99t.
Frankly I am not sure that any of this makes a=C2=A0huge=C2=A0difference. T=
he bond market and the syndicated loan market both involve mainly sophistic=
ated institutional investors; most companies do not raise money by selling =
bonds=C2=A0or=C2=A0loans to retail investors. Most bond offerings are exemp=
t from securities registration under private-placement rules, and all syndi=
cated loans would be too, even if they were securities. If you lie in your =
loan documents probably someone can sue you for fraud (bank fraud?), even i=
f they can=E2=80=99t sue you for=C2=A0securities=C2=A0fraud, and even if th=
e standards are a bit different. Most bonds don=E2=80=99t trade on national=
 securities exchanges anyway, so it=E2=80=99s not like making loans securit=
ies would require them to trade on exchanges.
Still there are some differences that probably matter a lot to, like, the l=
awyers supporting loan arranging and trading desks (and electronic loan tra=
ding platforms). Declaring loans securities would cause various sorts of di=
sruption. My=20
favorite difference is that you=E2=80=99re allowed to trade loans with insi=
de information,=C2=A0sort of, while you are=C2=A0not allowed to trade secur=
ities with inside information: Insider trading in securities is illegal, wh=
ile banks were historically=C2=A0supposed=C2=A0to be intimately familiar wi=
th the nonpublic details of their borrowers=E2=80=99 businesses, and if you=
 bought a loan from the bank that made it then of course you would assume t=
hat the bank knew things that you didn=E2=80=99t. (These days, syndicated l=
oan markets have =E2=80=9Cpublic side=E2=80=9D traders, people at hedge fun=
ds and elsewhere who trade both loans and bonds and so don=E2=80=99t get in=
side information, and =E2=80=9Cprivate side=E2=80=9D traders, people at ban=
ks and other lenders who deal directly with companies and get inside inform=
ation.)
What does=C2=A0not=C2=A0happen, in syndicated loan deals, is that banks sel=
l them to retail investors without any disclosure and then say =E2=80=9Chah=
a, not a security, you can=E2=80=99t sue us!=E2=80=9D This is all an instit=
utional market.
Anyway, some institutional investors in a loan deal didn=E2=80=99t like how=
 the deal worked out, so they=20
sued JPMorgan Chase & Co., an arranger of the loan, for securities fraud. J=
PMorgan said, nope, not securities, so not securities fraud. (The case is c=
alled Kirschner v. JPMorgan, and we have talked about it a   couple of  tim=
es over the years.)
The standard view is that syndicated loans are not securities, and a federa=
l court agreed with JPMorgan and dismissed the case.=C2=A0The investors app=
ealed. The federal appeals court had the bright idea of asking the US Secur=
ities and Exchange Commission, which after all regulates securities, for it=
s views. The SEC is=C2=A0very keenly interested in the exact contours of wh=
at is and is not a security, so you might expect it to enthusiastically ans=
wer the court=E2=80=99s question.   But, nope:

The Securities and Exchange Commission said it is =E2=80=9Cnot in a positio=
n to file=E2=80=9D a brief giving its view on whether leveraged loans are s=
ecurities, sidestepping a request to weigh in on a long-running lawsuit tha=
t may have major implications for the $1.4 trillion market for risky debt.
A three-judge US Court of Appeals panel had sought the SEC=E2=80=99s view o=
n the question as it weighs a decision in a case that could upend the lever=
aged buyout machine and a decades-old market riskier companies rely on for =
financing. The SEC=E2=80=99s filing had been hotly anticipated because the =
court was expected to lean heavily on its opinion, legal experts earlier to=
ld Bloomberg.
=E2=80=9CDespite diligent efforts to respond to the Court=E2=80=99s order a=
nd provide the Commission=E2=80=99s views, the staff is unfortunately not i=
n a position to file a brief on behalf of the Commission in this matter. We=
 greatly appreciate the Court=E2=80=99s indulgence and regret any inconveni=
ence this may have caused the Court or the parties,=E2=80=9D according to t=
he letter filed on Tuesday and signed by SEC General Counsel Megan Barbero.
The panel that=E2=80=99s deciding the case, Kirschner v. JPMorgan, now will=
 likely need to decide the case without input from the agency. If the court=
 rules that the loan at the heart of the case was a security, it could ushe=
r sweeping new regulations into the market.

Ahahahaha what is going on here? I think it is impossible to read this with=
out reference to the SEC=E2=80=99s   crackdown on cryptocurrencies. The SEC=
 has been aggressive in asserting that   virtually all crypto tokens are se=
curities and subject to SEC regulation, but=C2=A0that position has gotten a=
 lot of criticism from the crypto industry and some politicians. And last w=
eek the SEC had a strange but important loss in court, when   a federal dis=
trict court ruled that Ripple=E2=80=99s XRP token sometimes is and sometime=
s isn=E2=80=99t a security.
  [2]
=C2=A0The SEC will presumably appeal that decision. There is a live=C2=A0co=
ntroversy over what securities laws apply to crypto, and the SEC is pushing=
 a maximal approach.
Mostly that approach consists of litigating crypto cases, but the SEC tries=
 to stay on-message generally. We   talked last week about an SEC enforceme=
nt action against a company that sells shares of Ferraris and art and stuff=
. There was no crypto involved, but I argued that the SEC pursued that case=
 as a relevant precedent: =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not just crypto, lots of wa=
ys to package speculative investments are illegal securities offerings,=E2=
=80=9D was the rough message.=C2=A0
And here comes a court asking it if some=C2=A0other=C2=A0thing is a securit=
y, a thing that has been treated as=C2=A0not=C2=A0a security for decades. W=
hat can the SEC do?
=09It can say =E2=80=9Cno, syndicated loans are not securities.=E2=80=9D Bu=
t then it is conceding that some investment opportunities are not securitie=
s; it is giving crypto people some precedents to argue that=C2=A0their=C2=
=A0things are not securities.
  [3]
=C2=A0Also it looks bad politically: The SEC is being maximalist about what=
 counts as a security when it goes after crypto upstarts, but it is letting=
 JPMorgan avoid securities laws. If you are a crypto-friendly politician, t=
hat looks like favoritism for the big incumbents at the expense of crypto i=
nnovators.=09It can say =E2=80=9Cyes, syndicated loans are securities.=E2=
=80=9D But then it might lose! Syndicated loans have=C2=A0not, historically=
, been treated as securities, so it is not obvious that the court would agr=
ee with the SEC=E2=80=99s view. If the SEC argued that they are securities,=
 it would give ammunition to critics who say that it is trying to expand it=
s jurisdiction in ways no one previously thought appropriate. And of course=
 on the other side would be most of the big banks and investment firms: A l=
ot of respectable traditional financial firms would disagree with the SEC a=
nd fight back against it. It=E2=80=99s one thing to be aggressive against c=
rypto upstarts; it=E2=80=99s another thing to fight JPMorgan.

Neither is a great outcome. Also, to be clear, I don=E2=80=99t know=C2=A0wh=
at the SEC actually thinks:=C2=A0My wild guess would be that SEC Chair Gary=
 Gensler, who has led the SEC=E2=80=99s maximalist push, probably does thin=
k that everything is a security and would like to regulate bank loans, whil=
e a lot of SEC staffers are used to the status quo and think that regulatin=
g bank loans as securities would solve no problems and would create new one=
s. But I don=E2=80=99t think this matters that much: Whatever the SEC think=
s in its heart of hearts, it has no interest in talking=C2=A0about it, now.
I should say that a view like =E2=80=9Cno, syndicated loans are not securit=
ies, but all crypto tokens are=E2=80=9D would be totally coherent. For one =
thing, a crypto token really is often a=C2=A0speculative investment in a st=
artup business promoted by its founder, in a way that a bank loan is not.
  [4]
 But also, the reason the SEC wants to regulate crypto tokens as securities=
 is that=C2=A0they are sold broadly to retail investors, while syndicated l=
oans are not. If your concern is protecting retail investors from risky spe=
culative investments promoted with wild promises, treating crypto tokens as=
 securities probably helps you achieve your goal, while treating syndicated=
 loans as securities is irrelevant.

