<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traditionally, in US law, a bond is a security=
=C2=A0and a bank loan is not. If a company borrows money by selling bonds t=
o the bond market, it has to follow securities laws; the theory is that bon=
ds are sold publicly to lots of different unrelated investors, who will wan=
t the disclosures and legal protections of the securities laws. If a compan=
y borrows money by taking out bank loans, it does not have to follow securi=
ties laws; the theory is that loans are negotiated directly with a handful =
of banks who are sophisticated, know the company well and do not really nee=
d the protections of securities laws.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In modern markets=C2=A0that is not particularl=
y true. =E2=80=9CBank loans,=E2=80=9D these days, are <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32142671.258409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDQtMTAvdWJlci1pcy1vbi1pdHMtd2F5LX=
RvLWFuLWlwbz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzIwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0b=
V9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA3MjAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1=
ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB877e473b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  often syndicated loans</a>=
 sold to hundreds of investors, many of whom are hedge funds or collaterali=
zed-loan-obligation managers or otherwise not banks. Bonds, meanwhile, are =
mostly sold to big institutional investors too, and there is some overlap b=
etween the loan and bond investor bases. It seems a bit strange and outdate=
d to treat loans and bonds differently, and so you sometimes come across pe=
ople who argue that loans should be securities, or people who are surprised=
 to learn that they aren=E2=80=99t.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Frankly I am not sure that any of this makes a=
=C2=A0<em>huge=C2=A0</em>difference. The bond market and the syndicated loa=
n market both involve mainly sophisticated institutional investors; most co=
mpanies do not raise money by selling bonds=C2=A0<em>or=C2=A0</em>loans to =
retail investors. Most bond offerings are exempt from securities registrati=
on under private-placement rules, and all syndicated loans would be too, ev=
en if they were securities. If you lie in your loan documents probably some=
one can sue you for fraud (bank fraud?), even if they can=E2=80=99t sue you=
 for=C2=A0<em>securities=C2=A0</em>fraud, and even if the standards are a b=
it different. Most bonds don=E2=80=99t trade on national securities exchang=
es anyway, so it=E2=80=99s not like making loans securities would require t=
hem to trade on exchanges.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still there are some differences that probably=
 matter a lot to, like, the lawyers supporting loan arranging and trading d=
esks (and electronic loan trading platforms). Declaring loans securities wo=
uld cause various sorts of disruption. My <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/32142671.258409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTItMTYvdGhlLXNlYy1oYXMtYmlnLXBsYW5zP2NtcGlkPU=
JCRDA3MjAyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0d=
GVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDcyMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB6e91160e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">
favorite difference</a> is that <em>you=E2=80=99re allowed to trade loans w=
ith inside information,=C2=A0</em>sort of, while you are=C2=A0<em>not allow=
ed to trade securities with inside information: </em>Insider trading in sec=
urities is illegal, while banks were historically=C2=A0<em>supposed=C2=A0</=
em>to be intimately familiar with the nonpublic details of their borrowers=
=E2=80=99 businesses, and if you bought a loan from the bank that made it t=
hen of course you would assume that the bank knew things that you didn=E2=
=80=99t. (These days, syndicated loan markets have =E2=80=9Cpublic side=E2=
=80=9D traders, people at hedge funds and elsewhere who trade both loans an=
d bonds and so don=E2=80=99t get inside information, and =E2=80=9Cprivate s=
ide=E2=80=9D traders, people at banks and other lenders who deal directly w=
ith companies and get inside information.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What does=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>happen, in sy=
ndicated loan deals, is that banks sell them to retail investors without an=
y disclosure and then say =E2=80=9Chaha, not a security, you can=E2=80=99t =
sue us!=E2=80=9D This is all an institutional market.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway, some institutional investors in a loan=
 deal didn=E2=80=99t like how the deal worked out, so they <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32142671.258409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMDgtMDIvdHJ1c3RlZS1hbGxlZ2VzLWpwb=
W9yZ2FuLWNoYXNlLWZhaWxlZC10by1kaXNjbG9zZS1iaWxsaW5nLXByb2JlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA3=
MjAyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV=
