ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked last week</a> about an SE=
C enforcement action against a company that sells shares of Ferraris and ar=
t and stuff. There was no crypto involved, but I argued that the SEC pursue=
d that case as a relevant precedent: =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not just crypto,=
 lots of ways to package speculative investments are illegal securities off=
erings,=E2=80=9D was the rough message.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And here comes a court asking it if some=C2=A0=
<em>other=C2=A0</em>thing is a security, a thing that has been treated as=
=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>a security for decades. What can the SEC do?</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It can say =E2=80=9Cno, syndicated lo=
ans are not securities.=E2=80=9D But then it is conceding that some investm=
ent opportunities are not securities; it is giving crypto people some prece=
dents to argue that=C2=A0<em>their=C2=A0</em>things are not securities.<a c=
lass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpare=
nt !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Also it looks bad politically: The SEC is being maximalist about =
what counts as a security when it goes after crypto upstarts, but it is let=
ting <em>JPMorgan </em>avoid securities laws. If you are a crypto-friendly =
politician, that looks like favoritism for the big incumbents at the expens=
e of crypto innovators.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It can say=
 =E2=80=9Cyes, syndicated loans are securities.=E2=80=9D But then it might =
lose! Syndicated loans have=C2=A0<em>not</em>, historically, been treated a=
s securities, so it is not obvious that the court would agree with the SEC=
=E2=80=99s view. If the SEC argued that they are securities, it would give =
ammunition to critics who say that it is trying to expand its jurisdiction =
in ways no one previously thought appropriate. And of course on the other s=
ide would be most of the big banks and investment firms: A lot of respectab=
le traditional financial firms would disagree with the SEC and fight back a=
gainst it. It=E2=80=99s one thing to be aggressive against crypto upstarts;=
 it=E2=80=99s another thing to fight JPMorgan.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Neither is a great outcome. Also, to be clear,=
 I don=E2=80=99t know=C2=A0<em>what the SEC actually thinks:=C2=A0</em>My w=
ild guess would be that SEC Chair Gary Gensler, who has led the SEC=E2=80=
=99s maximalist push, probably <em>does </em>think that everything is a sec=
urity and would like to regulate bank loans, while a lot of SEC staffers ar=
e used to the status quo and think that regulating bank loans as securities=
 would solve no problems and would create new ones. But I don=E2=80=99t thi=
nk this matters that much: Whatever the SEC thinks in its heart of hearts, =
it has no interest in <em>talking=C2=A0</em>about it, now.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I should say that a view like =E2=80=9Cno, syn=
dicated loans are not securities, but all crypto tokens are=E2=80=9D would =
be totally coherent. For one thing, a crypto token really is often a=C2=A0s=
peculative investment in a startup business promoted by its founder, in a w=
ay that a bank loan is not.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importa=
nt; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> But also, the reason the SEC wants to regulate crypto tokens as securi=
ties is that=C2=A0<em>they are sold broadly to retail investors</em>, while=
 syndicated loans are not. If your concern is protecting retail investors f=
rom risky speculative investments promoted with wild promises, treating cry=
pto tokens as securities probably helps you achieve your goal, while treati=
ng syndicated loans as securities is irrelevant.</p>
